<BaseLayout
  title="Why Diataxis fits README.llm vNext"
  description="A conceptual explanation of how Diataxis can complement README.llm vNext without becoming a compliance requirement."
  eyebrow="Explanation"
>
  <p>
    README.llm vNext and Diataxis operate at different layers. Diataxis helps
    structure human-facing documentation by intent; README.llm vNext structures
    machine-discoverable documentation for retrieval and semantic precision.
  </p>

  <h2>Why they complement each other</h2>
  <p>
    Diataxis provides a human information architecture with four lenses:
    tutorials, how-to guides, reference, and explanation. README.llm vNext can
    sit alongside that structure by adding manifests, metadata, and explicit
    contracts for machine consumers.
  </p>

  <h2>Why it is non-normative</h2>
  <p>
    The standard should not require a single human-facing content model. Some
    libraries will prefer Diataxis; others will use domain-specific structures.
    Treating Diataxis as recommended guidance keeps the standard compatible with
    established documentation practice without making it mandatory.
  </p>

  <h2>Why the site uses it anyway</h2>
  <p>
    This site demonstrates the four lenses directly so the recommendation is not
    just theoretical. The human-facing routes are grouped by intent, while the
    machine-facing artifacts remain independently discoverable.
  </p>
</BaseLayout>
